Is this valid use case from host or error case?

Yeah, this commit in general feels like a bit of a workaround for a host firmware bug? Sometimes it's not possible to fix the bug, and instead work around it, but it would be good to have more info in the commit message on why that's the case. This type of if/else code is what causes bugs because it's difficult to test all the different paths.

This is not a bug in the host but during internal failure recovery they report pending dumps once again, when we already have an entry another one will be a duplicate and confuse the users, to prevent that BMC code needs to filter such duplicate notifications, will update the commit message
Done
please update commit message with additional details recomented here.

can you please check the commit message, the reason is already there

This issue arises particularly during internal failure recovery
in the host, where it notifies all the pending dumps again.
In cases where entries are already available for such dumps on the BMC,
duplicate entries may be created, potentially leading to confusion
for users. This change prevents the creation of new entries if an entry
already exists for the same dump.
Better to starting  lg2, for new logs.
Done

So just to confirm, if it has the same ID, but it's not completed, the expected behavior is to create a new dump with the same ID? The code will all handle that ok? Or do we need to delete the dump with the same ID first?
Another dump with same name won't come because only one dump at a time and this dump needs to be deleted to create a new one

It just feels like a possible bug. We get into some situation where the dumpId is present in the entries but for whatever reason it was not Completed. Would everything work ok with the below code as-is in this scenario or should we have an else clause to this to ensure we clean it up?

This dump is not stored in the BMC and Host sends the message only after the completion, so the source dump id is present only for a completed dump(please don't confuse it with the id BMC assigned, this is assigned by the host)

I feel it is very similar to what we do in the restart of applications, the notifications are sent again to be filtered somewhere else. 


This happens rarely, but if we don't filter, we will have the same dump with two entries.

What we can do in `else` is to add a trace saying ignored a duplicate entry

Yeah, instead of trying to be absolutely sure the host never sends down a dump that does not get into a Completed state, lets just at least leave a bread crumb for us in the journal doing an "else if (sysEntry->sourceDumpId() == dumpId) {lg2::info ("System dump entry with ... is already present but not Completed"}" and then just continue. At least we'll have a debug point if it were to ever happen.
Done

As per our design, a dump is marked as completed only when both the dump id and size are successfully received from the host. so, we only have one active dump at any given time. Because a new dump cannot be generated unless the existing one is deleted first, the possibility of having an incomplete dump entry with the same id is nearly negligible.

But, as per our discussion, to catch any errors, I will add an 'else' clause for logging incomplete dump entry with the same id is detected.
Rebase this commit chain with latest.
Is this a common occurrence? If not, a "lg2::info" indicating the delete is occurring could be useful.
this is a very rare scenario, will add a log, that will be helpful
Ack
